England","Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, England":"Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Eydon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Eyden  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Eyden","meanings":["English: locative name from Eydon (Northants)."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]},{"name":"Maude","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Maud  , the usual spelling of the name in North America."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Matilda Maude de Eydon was born in 1200, in Scotland, her father, Geoffrey De Eydon, was 20 and her mother, Mrs. De Hyden, was 14. She married Captain Hugh de Hynton of Hinton-Woodford in 1240, in Woodford, Gloucestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1294, in Woodford, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 94."},"et":{"1200–1294":"1200–1294","1200–1280":"1200–1280","1225–1287":"1225–1287","1180–1209":"1180–1209","1187–Female":"1187–Surnud","1225":"1225","1200":"1200","1287":"1287","1187":"1187","about 1225":"umbes 1225","1240":"1240","1294":"1294","after 1287":"pärast 1287","1209":"1209","1280":"1280","1180":"1180","Forest of Dean, Gloucestershire, England":"Forest of Dean, Gloucestershire, England","Hinton Woodford, Northamptonshire, England":"Woodford, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Scotland":"Scotland","Woodford, Northamptonshire, England":"Woodford, Northamptonshire, England","Woodford, Gloucestershire, England":"Woodford, Gloucestershire, England","Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, England":"Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1200–1294":"1200–1294","1200–1280":"1200–1280","